Peter, I agree too. This is so obviously verse. Apart from the fact it has
rhythm and meter, the language itself is poetic, has poetic reversals (such
as &quot;and then dreams he&quot;) and looks as though it were written in a particular
way to fit the pentameter. It also makes no sense that part but not all of
it would be prose, as in the second version. It's one of my favourite
Shakespearean speeches, and I remember being enchanted by it when I was
twelve, partly because it *lilts.*

